{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"314"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/314"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.08,0.29,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107508"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/314"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107508"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of increasing left iliac fossa pain. He has never experienced similar symptoms before. He has a medical history of sigmoid diverticular disease, mechanical aortic valve replacement, and a recent chest infection. His medications include warfarin and amoxicillin which was started one week ago for the chest infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. His abdomen is tender in the left iliac fossa with guarding but no rebound tenderness. The remainder of the abdominal examination is normal. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rectus sheath haematoma","Sigmoid appendagitis","Diverticulitis","Pericolic abscess","Pneumoperitoneum"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute left-sided abdominal pain while anticoagulated with warfarin. The CT scan demonstrates a \u003Cstrong\u003Erectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E, showing blood confined within the rectus muscle sheath. Two key risk factors are present: anticoagulation (present in 70% of cases) and recent coughing which can tear epigastric vessels during rectus muscle contraction. Management typically involves reversal of anticoagulation if severe, and supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid appendagitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a fatty mass adjacent to the sigmoid colon on CT, which is not seen here. This condition results from inflammation of an epiploic appendage and usually causes self-limiting pain without systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show colonic wall thickening, inflammatory changes in the surrounding fat, and possibly complications like abscess formation. These features are absent on the CT scan. Additionally, patients typically present with fever and altered bowel habits, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericolic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a fluid collection with rim enhancement and surrounding inflammatory changes. The CT shows a haematoma rather than an abscess collection. Abscesses typically develop as a complication of diverticulitis or appendicitis and are associated with systemic inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumoperitoneum\u003C/strong\u003E would be visible as free air under the diaphragm or in the peritoneal cavity on CT, which is not present here. This finding indicates bowel perforation and would typically present with severe generalised peritonitis rather than localised pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile amoxicillin does not significantly interact with warfarin, many other medications can affect warfarin metabolism and increase bleeding risk. The combination of anticoagulation and a precipitating factor like coughing makes rectus sheath haematoma a classic presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rectus sheath haematoma commonly occurs in anticoagulated patients, particularly with precipitating factors like coughing.","Abdominal pain in an anticoagulated patient should make one consider rectus sheath haematoma.","CT imaging is diagnostic for rectus sheath haematoma, showing blood confined within the muscle sheath."],"references":["Hatjipetrou A, Anyfantakis D, Kastanakis M. Rectus sheath hematoma: A review of the literature. Int J Surg 2015;13:267-71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25529279/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"314"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15764"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20590"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15764"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e195d36-80a5-4825-bfb7-6042d1dd57a7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e195d36-80a5-4825-bfb7-6042d1dd57a7.jpg","isPr